{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"10aeb8e8-77f2-4f8f-a775-546659193775","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\nHere are your best options for analyzing a `.dmp` file:\n\n**1. `dotnet-dump analyze` (cross-platform, recommended)**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n**2. `lldb` with SOS (Linux/macOS)**\n```bash\nlldb --core <your-file.dmp>\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nclrstack\npe\n```\n\n**3. Visual Studio or WinDbg (Windows)**\nOpen the `.dmp` directly in Visual Studio or load SOS in WinDbg.\n\n---\n\n**Quick triage steps:**\n1. Run `dotnet-dump analyze your.dmp`\n2. Type `pe` to print the exception that caused the crash\n3. Type `clrstack` to see the managed stack trace\n4. Type `threads` then `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` to inspect other threads\n\nWould you like me to install `dotnet-dump` and walk through the analysis with your file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6b700445-f9ae-49d1-b418-edaa8791ee42","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So I should not invoke that skill.\n\nI can help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":449,"requestId":"7640:343F6:1A6BA35:1DF68A9:69FE93A4"},"id":"62dbbcc8-6bb4-449b-af78-463c2e6dfe08","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:53:52.054Z","parentId":"cc0c9794-423b-4d10-887a-bbd2cba5341c"}
